@missingtwins: Hi there. What kind of OS and browser are you using? What did you see and hear?

Video Streaming has never been easier.

[New APIs](https://github.com/MuxZeroNet/ZeroMux/blob/master/loader/js/streamer/zeromux-streamer.js#L10) added to ZeroMux.

```js
// all about your video file
var args = streamArgs(
    "path/to/file.json",
    "path/to/moov.box",
    'video/mp4; codecs="avc1.______, mp4a.__._"'
);

// your video element
var videoElement = document.getElementById('video-tag');
// your callback function
var callback = function(obj)
{
    console.log(obj); // mysterious object logged to console
};

// download and pipe data to media element
downloadAndAttach(args, videoElement, callback);
```

I know you guys don't want to code, so I made a [simple video player](http://127.0.0.1:43110/Me.ZeroNetwork.bit/?Post/1RedkCkVaXuVXrqCMpoXQS29bwaqsuFdL/1LxkfGxtWhktAJ5WJ9ZnKxksTSH37qm8cC/1485055780).

Emscripten is very interesting. You can write synchronous code that does asynchronous operations, and compile your code with Emterpreter that really pauses execution when necessary.
```
./emcc async.c -o html.html -s EMTERPRETIFY=1 -s EMTERPRETIFY_ASYNC=1
```

Before every read and seek operation, your C code can set a `_functionReturned` flag to `false` and call an async JavaScript function that finds data for you. For example, the `read` method of ZeroMux stream. Then go into a `sleep` loop until the `_functionReturned` flag has been set back to `true`.

Furthermore, your JavaScript program has direct access to the virtual memory, so you can share buffers across C and JavaScript.
```js
char *a  = malloc(4);
EM_ASM_({
    readFrom($0, $1, $2);
}, 123456, a, 4);
```

